al microscope.','Number of students: One.','8-110 weeks'),(134,'CHE','Vinaykumar A Juvekar','Sliding friction of elastomers on hard surfaces',' Elstomers-hars surface friction is important in many applications such\r\nas friction of rubber tyres on road, processing of polymer,contact\r\nbetween prostheses and tissus etc. We are trying to study variety of\r\nphenomena occurring during the sliding process using a tribometer. It\r\nmeasures the force of friction as a function of the sliding velocity.\r\nWe have developed a model based on population balance of bonds. We wish\r\nto use PDMS blocks sliding on glass surface coated with SAM and wish to\r\nmodel relxation and stick-slip phenomena.','Number of students: One.','8-10 weeks'),(135,'MET','R. O. Dusane, Ankur Kumar','Impedance behavior of Supercapacitor',' It would be related to thin film deposition process. You can expect to have significant amount of hands on experiences in the lab especially characterization techniques. ','','2 months'),(136,'MET','Somnath Basu','Plasma Spray coatings for dental implants  ','                                                                                                                    \r\nOptimization of plasma spraying process parameters and powder \r\ncharacteristics for achieving consistent coatings. The coated components\r\n would eventually be used as dental ororthopedicimplants.\r\n\r\n','','2 months'),(137,'MET','Parag Bhargava','Mathematical modelling of dye sensitized solar cells','','Self driven, patient, desire to learn','1st may - 30th june (8 weeks)'),(138,'MET','Parag Bhargava','Chemical mechanical planarization of films on silicon wafers','','',''),(139,'MET','Parag Bhargava','Glass and glass ceramic materials ','','',''),(140,'MET','Parag Bhargava','Characterization of ceramic materials ','','',''),(141,'MET','Parag Bhargava','Gelation of ceramic materials','','',''),(142,'CSE','Sudarshan','Online evaluation: beyond MCQs','MCQs are an old technology tied to OMR sheets. With online tests we can do a LOT more.  Examples: 1) Give steps of a proof plus extra junk in random order.  Ask students to pick the   correct steps of the proof in order.    Marks can be based on overlap between the   orders, with random choice getting an expected 0 (how to do this?  good question   for JEE problem crackers.) 2) Add a small drawing editor, and ask students to create drawings as required, by   selecting from a question dependent palate (e.g. atoms, nodes in a search tree)   and linking them up by appropriate edges.  The editor will not allow arbitrary   drawings, so grading can again be automated by graph matching of some form. 3) Fill in the blanks to create a program/derivation/grammatically correct passages/..    with multiple choices for each blank.  This can be done even with MCQ, but the    visual effect of having a complete program/derivation/passage on screen will ease the process. 4) The obvious things like:  entering numerical answers, having far more than 4 choices using     a drop down list, 5) .. add your own ideas here The goal of this project is to create software that allows questions of the new types to be created, stored in some format, and tests administered from that format.Interfaces for all the above are web interfaces with Javascript.','knowledge of Java and HTML, knowledge of Javascript and databases would be a non-essential plus.    Good grades in programming courses. Honorarium subject to satisfactory completion of assigned tasks ',''),(143,'CIVIL','A Rastogi','Groundwater modelling using Matlab ','Working on a problem statement involving modelling of groundwater table using given parameters. Can work from Anywhere (not necessarily in lab), but Weekly reporting of work is essential','Must know Matlab,Must have read Chapter 9 of the book Numerical Groundwater Hydrology by A Rastogi (Available in Library) 2nd year students and preferably 3rd year students.','2 Months');
