re asked to write an essay. Essays written by these students aze evaluated by a panel of judges and, based on their performance, candidates are shortlisted for the final round. Those shortlisted are invited for an interview. The 10 best engineering students become Aditya Birla Scholars. The interviews are conducted by an eminent panel of business luminaries and academicians in Mumbai. Invited candidates are given an allowance to cover expenses on travel and accommodation.\n\n\n=== OPJEMS Scholarship ===\n\nYearly Scholarship: INR 65, 000\n\nStudents from both the following categories will be considered in the shortlist:\n\n2 toppers from each batch from the following streams for all 4 years: Civil Engineering, Electrical Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, Metallurgical Engineering\n\nTop 12 students from each batch (any specialization or stream) for all 4 years.\n\n For instance:\n\nMr Kumar could be one of the top 2 students from Civil Engineering and also be the one of the top 12 students for his batch. In this case, his name should appear only under the 1st category. For the 2nd category, another top student from his batch should be identified to meet the number of 12.\n\nMr Kumar could be one of the top 2 students from mechanical engineering but not be one of the top 12 students for his batch. In this case, his name should appear once in the list ( as a part of category 1).\n\nMr Kumar could be 1 of the top 12 students in his batch but not belong to civil, electrical, mechanical or metallurgical streams. In this case, his name should appear once in the list (as a part of category 2)\n\nA total of 112 students selected from 33 institutes would be awarded the OPJEMS Scholarship. The final scholarship will be awarded based on the score of the individual in the online test (assessing him or her on leadership behaviors), and personal interview in the final stage. Equal weightage will be given for the online test and the interview.\n\n\n=== Rajshri Shahu Maharaj Scholarship ===\n\nAwarded to 100 Students belonging to Scheduled Castes for Education in Reknowned Educational Institutions in the Country.\n\nhttp://www.pwd.maharashtra.gov.in/pdf/contry.pdf\n\n\n=== KPMG Foundation Scholarship ===\n\n\n=== KVPY Scholarship ===\n\nhttp://www.kvpy.org.in\n\n\n=== Merit Scholarship from Ministry of Steel ===\n\nMinistry of Steel Scholarship for 5 UG students of MEMS Department  for 5 years.\n\n\n=== INSPIRE Scholarship ===\n\nThis scheme offers 10,000 scholarships every year @ Rs.80,000/- each for undertaking Bachelor and Masters level education in the Natural & Basic sciences, possessing any of the following criteria:\n \n[A]	\nStudents who happen to be among the top 1% in 12th standard at their respective Board Examinations and are pursuing courses in Natural and Basic sciences at the B.Sc. or Integrated M.Sc. levels. Courses are not included other than Natural and Basic sciences in the current scheme in view of the focus on research in Basic sciences.\n \n[B]	\nStudents who have secured in the Joint Entrance Examination of IIT top 10,000 ranks, AIEEE (top 10,000 ranks) plus those clearing AIPMT (top 10,000 ranks), and who also opt to study Natural and Basic sciences in any academic institute or university leading to graduate and post-graduate degree, would be eligible for scholarship.','utf-8'),(9,'== Institute Scholarships ==\n\n=== Merit-cum-Means (MCM)===\n\nMerit-cum-Means scholarship is awarded @ Rs.1000/-per month with benefit of free tuition fee (Rs.25,000/-per semester) to a maximum of 25% of undergraduate students. For Dual degree, it is available only upto the 4th year.\n\nFor these scholarships, academic merit as well as means will be taken into account to determine eligibility.\n\n<b>Merit Criterion :</b> For new entrants (B.Tech. and Dual degree) their JEE-AIR will be the criterion. In case of students joining the 2-year M.Sc. programme, their performance in the admission test and interview will be considered for determining merit. In subsequent years, the corresponding criterion will be their academic performance during the preceding academic year.\n\n<b>Means Criterion :</b> The parental income is the basis for the `means\' criterion of the scholarship. At present students whose parents\' annual gross income from all sources does not exceed Rs.4,50,000/- are eligible to apply for Merit-cum-Means Scholarship. When a student applies for the scholarship for the first time, an Income Affidavit has to be submitted by the parent or guardian for the year preceding year of application for the scholarship. No fresh affidavit will be required for renewal of the scholarship in the subsequent years, till the completion of the programme to which the student is admitted. The scholarship will be renewed on a yearly basis provided the student fulfills all the terms and conditions for renewal of the scholarship.\n\nA student whose parental income falls below the prescribed limit at any point during the course of his programme (due to reasons such as retirement of the parent/guardian or due to any unforeseen circumstances) is eligible to be considered for an award of Merit-cum-Means scholarship from the month in which such situation arises. In this case also a fresh income affidavit, supported by acceptable documentary evidence needs to be submitted.\n\nThose students who have applied for the Private Trust Scholarships will not be considered for the Institute Merit-cum-Means Scholarships.\n\n<b>Free tuition: </b>In addition to those awarded Merit-cum-Means scholarships another 10% of students can get the benefit of free tuition only.\n\n<b>Free messing: </b>All SC/ST students are exempted from the payment of tuition fees. The facilities of free messing (only basic menu) and a pocket allowance of Rs.250/-p.m. will be granted to eligible SC/ST students. Such students are also eligible for exemption from the payment of hostel room rent, subject to the \'means\' criterion as mentioned before.\n\nThes