rying course required for the degree will be considered eligible for the award of medals. Here under-loading implies registering for number of credits which is less than that prescribed by the department for the particular semester.\n\n\n== Dr. Shankar Dayal Sharma Gold Medal for Academic and General Proficiency ==\n\nTheabovementionedawardwasinstitutedintheyear1994.\n\n<b>No. of medals: </b>1 for all UG and PG programmes\n\n<b>Criteria: </b>: 50%weightageshouldbegiventoacademicexcellence,whileother<br>\n50%forenrichmentofcommunityandnationallifethroughactivitiessuchassports,creative literature,musicandsocialwork,etc.','utf-8'),(21,'== Guidelines ==\n\nThe summer term is not a regular semester. However, during a summer term, an academic entity may offer a summer course to enable the students to clear their backlog courses and/or regular credit courses, subject to strict adherence to the following guidelines.\n                                                    \ni. The course instructor/(s)  / faculty/(ies)  should be willing to offer the course. The DUGC/HoD should recommend offering of such a summer course for consideration and approval of the Dean of Academic Programmes. The course is offered on approval of the Dean of Academic Programmes.\n\nii. The course is offered with adequate rigor and in the same manner as a regular semester course is offered. Students who have no backlog, can also register for a summer course, provided it is offered.\n\niii. The duration of the course is eight to ten weeks. The registration, examination and assessment and grading etc. are done in the same way as is done for regular semester courses. The total number of contact hours for the courses remains the same as that during the regular semesters, and therefore, the courses run at accelerated pace (for example 6 hours of instructions per week is expected for a 300 course).  \n\niv. The Instructors will award a FR grade to students who fail to adhere to 80% attendance for the summer course.\n\nv. At least 05 students should register for the summer course. The attendance record should be maintained and the minimum of 80% attendance is compulsory. A summer course may run for less than 5 students but in that case the professor will not be given the honorarium.\n\nvi. The number of credits registered by a student for summer course can be upto a maximum of 18 credits depending upon the backlog.\n\nvii. Courses offered in a summer term will be treated as equivalent to a regular semester  courses for all accounting purposes.\n\nviii. An amount of Rs 500/- per credit be charged for the summer course.  A typical 6 credit course requires a fee of Rs 3,000/-. SC, ST and PD students are given a fee waiver and do not have to pay any registration fees.\n\nix. A student can register for a course in advance i.e. a course, which is prescribed for a later semester, if the course instructor allows.\n\n\n== Procedure to run a Summer Course ==\n\nThe students who wish to take a summer course should first request the professor to take a summer course. Academic Office also sends a list of courses to department heads, which have more than 5 backlogs.\n\nThe students should stay in touch with the Department General Secretary for dept. courses and GSAA (UG) for institute courses.\n\nOnce the professor agrees, an application signed by the instructor with his consent to run the course is submitted to the Dean AP Office and once approved by Dean AP, it is forwarded to Academic Office to start the registration process.\n \n\n== Procedure to register for a Summer Course ==\n\nThe student should fill the UG-6 form available in Academic Office, take the signature of the course instructor(s), pay the fees at the Cash Section and submit the form along with the fee receipt at the Academic Office.\n\n\n== Procedure to register for > 18 credits ==\n\nThe student should request the Faculty Advisor (ARP Faculty Coordinator in case the student is under ARP) to allow him/her to take more than 18 credits. If the Faculty Advisor allows, the student should submit a written application with the Faculty Advisor\'s consent to the Dean AP Office. If the Dean allows, the student can register for the approved number of credits by showing the Dean AP approved application at the Academic Office.','utf-8'),(22,'Central Library occupies a place of pride in IIT Bombay and is an essential component of the institute\'s outstanding research and education mission. It is a most lively place on the campus providing a safe, comfortable and friendly environment that enables learning and advancement of knowledge, and promotes discovery and scholarship. The mission of the Central Library is to facilitate creation of new knowledge through acquisition, organization and dissemination of knowledge resources and providing for value added services. \n\n== Library Hours ==\n\nMonday through Friday: 0900    2300 hrs<br>\nMonday through Friday: 0900    0100 hrs (during mid-semester and end-semester examinations)<br>\nSaturdays / Sundays / Holidays        1000    1700 hrs<br>\nSaturdays / Sundays / Holidays        1000    0100 hrs (during mid-semester and end-semester examination)<br>\n\nThe library remains open on all days of the year except on National Holidays\n\n<b>Circulation Hours</b>:<br>\nMonday through Friday: 0900    2000 hrs<br>\nSaturday, Sunday & Holidays: 1100    1300  hrs<br>\nStudy room books issued for overnight, one hour before closing of the library on all days.\n\nA drop box has been placed near security check point.  Library members desiring to return the borrowed books can be dropped them in the box.\nBound volumes of journals, loose issues, pamphlets and standards are issued from first floor issue  counter on working days from 0900  1800 hrs.\n\n\n== Book Bank ==\n\n=== Technological Lending Library ===\n\nThe textbooks from the TLL Section are loaned out for one semester to the students whose parents income falls below the taxable limit. Eligible students may apply for books from the TLL as per the schedule announced by the Library. Students are invited to give their suggestions for keeping this collection updated on regular basis.\n\n=== Special Collection (BC) for SC/ST Students ===\n\nSelected books are made available for issue for a period of one semester to the students belonging to SC/ST. Eligible students may apply for books from the special collection as per the schedule announced by the Library.\n\n=== Study Room Books ===\n\nTextbooks recommended by the concerned faculty members for different courses are kept in the study room collection at the circulation counter for the period specified by the faculty. These books can be used in the library against Identity Card. Only one book can be issued to a student against Identity Card, for an overnight, to be returned the next day by 2 p.m. A late fee of Rs. 25.00 per day is charged for overdue books (Rs. 50/- during examination period).\n\n\n== Circulation ==\n\nCategory  of  Membership_________________________________________________No. of Books____Period of Loan<br>\nStudents B. Tech (up to 3rd year)________________________________________10______________30 days<br>\nStudents B. Tech (Final) / M. Sc /M. Tech / M. Des / M. Mgt. /Ph D_______15______________30 days<br>\nFaculty,t officers_______________________________________________________30______________One semester<br>\n\n\n<b>Circulation Rules</b><br>\nGeneral books are issued to all eligible members as per their entitlements.\n\nThe readers should check the book thoroughly for missing pages, chapters, pictures etc., while borrowing the book.\n\nNo book in damaged condition will be accepted from the reader. Mutilated or spoiled books will have to be replaced by the borrower.\n\nBooks issued will not be accepted back on the same day.\n\nReader can claim books (reserve) already issued, at the circulation counter.\nLoss of book must be reported immediately. Late fees, if any, will be charged till the loss of book is reported. If the original library book is returned after reporting it lost, the fine will be calculated till the date of its return.\n\nFor the rules for replacement of lost book kindly contact the Circulation Section.\n\nOne reader can put maximum 3 claims. A book can have maximum 4 claims.\n\nClaimed books are kept reserved for the claimant for 7 days from the date of return by previous borrower. Study room books should be claimed before 2.00 P.M. A student can claim maximum 3 books and a book can have maximum 2 claims. Books are reissued only if there are no claims.\nThe borrowing facility can be withdrawn or restricted in case of misbehaviour or misuse of the library.\n \n<b>Issue/Return Timing:</b>\n\nGeneral / Reference books - Monday-Friday: 9.00 A.M. to 8.00 P.M. and on Saturday, Sunday & Holidays 11.00 A.M. to 1.00 P.M.<br>\nBound volumes of journals, loose issues, pamphlets and standards are issued from first floor issue counter on working days from 9.00 A.M. to 6.00 P.M.<br>\nStudy Room Books are also issued for overnight One hour before closing of the library i.e 10.00 - 10.30 pm on Working days & 4.00 - 4.30 pm on Holidays<br>\n\n\n== Inter-Library Loan ==\n\nThe Central Library offers inter-library loan service to its users for the books and periodicals not available in the IIT Library by procuring them from other libraries within Mumbai. The IIT Bombay Library, in turn, also lends its resources to the libraries of other government and academic institutions on reciprocal basis. Under collaborative arrangement every Wednesday transport is available to visit BARC library. However, visitors need to register before hand for BARC security entry. The IIT Libraries already have an ongoing inter-library cooperation programme. Under the programme, the photocopies of research articles are exchanged on requests amongst several libraries.\n\nThe document procurement service is also made available from NISCAIR, British Library Lending Division and other document delivery services if the user is willing to bear the expenses involved.\n\n\n== Reference Section ==\n\nThe Library maintains a separate reference collection consisting of encyclopedias, dictionaries, directories, handbooks, technical data, almanacs, atlases, bibliographies, CD -ROMs, Audio and Video cassettes, etc. Reference books are marked  R and  Rare Reference  are marked RR. The collection marked \"RR are kept under lock and key.\n \nThe Reference Section also houses videos and DVDs. The  viewing facility is extended to the students, staff and faculty of the Institute from 9.30 a.m. to 5.30 p.m. on all working days.\n\nReaders may approach the Reference Desk for information or any assistance in the use of the Library Collections and Services. Users may also contact the Reference Division for CD ROM-based search services and web-based services.\n\n\n== Photocopying ==\n\nThe Central Library offers photocopying service to all its members, walk-in users and others.\n\nOnly single copy of journal articles and book chapters are provided for private study and research purpose.\n\nThe service is free to all the faculty memebers of IITB.  Please contact : Incharge, Bound Vols Section for details.\n\nPhoto Copy Charges: IITB Staff and students: Re. 0.50 per page A4 size, Re. 1.00 per page A3 size\n\nThe Photocopying Unit is on the mezanine floor and its timings are 9.30 am - 1.00 pm   and   2.00 pm - 5.30 pm from Monday to Friday\n\nCentral Library also supplies photocopies to Institutes / individuals by post on payment.\n\nCentral Library also operates DEPOSIT ACCOUNT facility for regular users to obtain copies quickly. For more details, please contact: Incharge, Periodical Section.\n\n\n== Late Fee Structure ==\n\nTypes of Material_______________________User____________First 15 Days___________16-30 Days______31-60 Days______Above 60 Days<br>\nBooks___________________________________All Categories__00.50 Paise /day________Re.1.00 /day____Rs.2.00 /day____Rs.5.00 /day<br>\nStudy Room Books issued over night______All categories__25.00 Per day<br>\n\nAny problem regarding Fine / No Dues please contact Circulation Section \n\nNote: Books Issue facility withheld, if fine beyond Rs. 30/- for Students and Rs. 100/- for faculty and staff\n\n\n== Ordering a Book ==\n\nA book can be ordered for the Library by filling up the Book Suggestion Form and getting the approval of the relevant faculty member.\n\n<b>Book Suggestion Form</b>: http://www.library.iitb.ac.in//index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=52\n\n\n== Important Links ==\n\n<b>Book Renewal:</b> http://asc.iitb.ac.in/academic/commjsp/index1.jsp <br>\n<b>Book Claim:</b> http://asc.iitb.ac.in/academic/commjsp/index1.jsp<br>\n<b>Book Search:</b> http://www.library.iitb.ac.in/newsearchbook/opac_s.php?m_memchk_flg=&m_summary=N <br>\n<b>Electronic Thesis Dissertations:</b> http://etd.library.iitb.ac.in/etd/index.jsp<br>\n<b>Book Suggestion Form:</b> http://www.library.iitb.ac.in//index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=52<br>\n<b>Digital Resources:</b> http://www.library.iitb.ac.in//index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=24&Itemid=38','utf-8'),(23,'Depending on the overall academic performance of a student till date, especially in the two preceding regular semesters (Autumn and Spring) registered, academic standing of the student is decided. \n\nCategorization of the academic standing of a student is as follows :\n\n<b>Category I</b> : Excellent Standing : A student who has no backlog courses (failed courses which have not been cleared subsequently or dropped courses), and has a CPI equal to or greater than 8.0, subject to having cleared the total number of credits prescribed up to that\nsemester in his/her discipline.\n\n<b>Category II</b> : Satisfactory Standing : A student who has registered for at least 18 credits in each of the two preceding regular registered semesters and not failed in any course in these two semesters.\n\n<b>Category III</b> : A student who has not failed in more than one course in the two preceding regular registered semesters, subject to having\nearned at least 18 credits in each of the semesters.\n\n<b>Category IV</b> : A student who has failed in more than one course in the two preceding regular registered semesters, but has earned at least 18 credits in each of the semesters.\n\n<b>Category V</b> : A student who has not earned at least 18 credits in either one of the previous two regular registered semesters.','utf-8'),(24,'An Institute Elective is a course, which can be taken in any department other than your own department (provided that the student fulfills the pre-requisites). This could be a course, which could have applications in your field of interest or it could be a course that you take out of sheer interest in the subject alone.\n\nNote: \n\n<b>1.</b> First year courses cannot be taken as Institute Electives as of Autumn semester 2012-13 onwards.\n\n<b>2.</b> If a student fails in an institute elective, he/she need not repeat the same course again. Another course can be taken.\n\n<b>3.</b> Some courses have pre-registration for institute electives. These courses have limited seats and the allotment is done on the basis of CPI.\n\n<b>4.</b> One can take permission from his/her faculty advisor and HoD if he/she wishes to do an institute elective in the department and get the application approved by Dean AP (which would then be submitted to the Academic Office).\n\n<b>5.</b> Minor courses can later be tagged as institute electives (For more details: [[Tagging]])\n\n<b>6.</b> In most cases, the students are required to do 2 institute electives - 12 credits. If a student wishes to take an 8 credit course, he can take special permission from the Dean AP if and only if his total credits for institute electives is equal to 12, i.e. the student will have to take a 4 credit course as his/her second institute elective. The total credits for institute electives should be as prescribed.','utf-8'),(25,'As approved on 6th July 2010, the following are the credit limits for different [[Academic Standing]]:\n\n<b>Category I</b>: 52\n\n<b>Category II</b>: 44\n\n<b>Category III</b>: 44\n\n<b>Category IV</b>: 36\n\n<b>Category V</b>: 24\n\n\nAny overload over and above this will have to be approved by the Faculty Advisor.','utf-8'),(26,'IIT Bombay students (UG and PG) are provided with financial assistance for conferences where a student\'s paper has been selected. A student is allowed to take this assistance only once in every 3 years. The funding will generally be not given to students within one year of their\njoining research programmes. The funding will not be given after submission of synopsis / thesis.\n\n== Process ==\n\nThe necessary documents along with the application form have to be submitted to the Dean AP Office. A committee comprising of the following members will approve the application and the amount:\n\nProf. S.K. Maiti (Convenor) <br>\nProf. V.M. Gadre<br>\nProf. A. Sanyal <br>\nProf. S.B. Patkar <br>\n\n== Scheme of Allotment ==\n\n== Application Form ==\n\nThe required documents are mentioned in the Application Form.\n\nhttp://www.iitb.ac.in/academic/downloadForms/appl_form20101april.pdf','utf-8'),(27,'Minor is an additional credential a student will earn if he/she does minimum 30 credits worth of additional learning in a discipline other than his/her major discipline of B.Tech/DD/Int. M.Sc. degree.\n\nStudents aspirations, on one hand, and the demands of the work place, on the other, have become highly diverse. Every student has specific abilities, interests and career goals. Employers too look for people with different combinations of competencies and flavours.\n\n== Eligibility ==\n\nFollowing students can register for minor courses every semester:\n\nB.Techs / Int. M.Sc.  Any B.Tech/Int. M.Sc.: Student with Academic Standing  Category I, II and III\n\nDDs  Category I\n\n\n== FAQs ==\n\n<b>Can I choose any courses in a dept. for a minor?<br></b>\nNo. You will have to choose from the list of courses prescribed by the dept.\n\n<b>Will it reflect on my degree?<br></b>\nThis will be mentioned in the Degree Certificate as Bachelor of Technology in xxx with Minor in yyy.\n\n<b>IfI ama DDstudent,canI do a minorinmyfinal year(9th and 10th semesters)?<br></b>\nAs ofnow, thisis not allowed, sincethe student is expected to focus on his/herDDPin thefinalyear.\n\n<b>Can Itake2 minors?<br></b>\nYes, ifyour faculty-advisor permits and you can find the slots to do so. Thereis also provision ofhaving6 to 12 credits ofminor as a project in somedepartment.\n\n<b>How is the allotment done?<br></b>\nThe allotment of minors (due to limited seats) is done on the basis of Core CPI after taking students preferences.\n\n<b>Does the Minor grade affect my SPI/CPI?<br></b>\nNo. When you complete your minor, a Minor CPI will reflect on your transcript. Before that, the courses will be counted as additional learning.\n\n<b>If we opt for a minor, and also for a Branch Change into the same branch, and are allotted both, how can the problem be resolved?<br></b>\nBC results will be intimated to you before the final date of minor registration.\n\n<b>IfI couldn\'t get a minorcoursefroma certaindepartmentthroughcentralizedcpi-based allotment, but in casetheinstructorallows meto jointhecourseas a credit course, Will the credits ofthecoursebeconsideredwhilemebeing consideredfora \"minor\"fromthatdepartment at theendof4 years?<br></b>\n1. Accordingto therules, entryto acourseoffered as a minor courseshouldbeonlythrough centralized CPI-based allotment.<br>\n2. Thus, ifyou want to takeaminor-offeredcourseas a creditcoursewith onlythepermission of theinstructor, this istechnicallynotallowed. You willhaveto approachthe Dean AP; each request willbetreated on acase-to-casebasis.','utf-8'),(28,'Honours is an additional credential a student will earn if s/he opts for  the extra 30 credits needed for this in  her/his own discipline. The concerned department specifies the course requirements for earning the Honours. \n\nAn honoris exactlylikeaminor except in that all honor couses areof thesame dept. \n\nHonorcourses areeitheradvanced level courses inyour discipline, or are courses designed to give you more exposure to different areas of your discipline.\n\nDDstudents haveto do honorbydefault. They are considered as their corecourses.\n\n== FAQs ==\n\n<b>Does the honours grade affect my CPI or is it just like the minor?<br></b>\nJust like minor (for DDs, compulsory honors courses will affect their Core CPI)\n\n<b>Is an honours beneficial even if one doesn\'t want to do research or further study?<br></b>\nYou want focussed knowledge in your department to take a job in a certain specialized area, so that you can compete with, say, an MTech who has specialized in the same area You want to do a job in a field different from that which you are studying in your department, but which requires similar (for example, quantitative) skills. You might like to show extremely strong skills by completing an honor successfully, thereby differentiating yourself from a batchmate who has not done that honor\n\n<b>Can I do a minor and honors?<br></b>\nYes, if your CPI > 8 (with no backlogs)\n\n<b>Will it appear on my degree?<br></b>\nYes  (similar to [[Minor]] )','utf-8'),(29,'<center><h2>Registration Rule Exceptions</h2>\n			<table border = 0  bgcolor=\'dddddd\' width = \'90%\' ><tr>\n<th bgcolor=\'aa77bb\'><font face=verdana color=white> Id </font></th>\n<th bgcolor=\'aa77bb\'><font face=verdana color=white> Code </font></th>\n<th bgcolor=\'aa77bb\'><font face=verdana color=white> Short Description </font></th>\n<th bgcolor=\'aa77bb\'><font face=verdana color=white> Long Description </font></th>\n<th bgcolor=\'aa77bb\'><font face=verdana color=white> Reference </font></th>\n<th bgcolor=\'aa77bb\'><font face=verdana color=white> Authority </font></th>\n<th bgcolor=\'aa77bb\'><font face=verdana color=white> Overridable </font></t