hese include all department compulsory courses and are also tagged as \"C\" on ASC. A core course may be replaced by an equivalent course in other departments but permission of the DUGC Convenor (HoD) will have to be sought before that. For example you can replace a Civil Structural Mechanics Course by an Aero Structural Mechanics Course if the Civil DUGC agrees to it</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department Electives</strong> - A student is required to also complete \"x\" number of electives where \"x\" varies from department to department which can be chosen from a bucket of courses as prescribed by the department. To take any course outside this bucket as a department elective will require consent of the HoD of that department. These courses are tagged as \"D\" on ASC</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Institute electives</strong> - Students in each curriculum are also given avenues to expand their breadth in terms of broad topics covered by having provisions for institute electives in the curriculum. Any course outside your parent department may be considered as an institute elective. You may also choose to do courses in your parent department as an institute elective but you require the permission of your facad and HoD for the same.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The total credits should amount to 252-262 credits.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For the Dual Degree Program, over and above this, students are required to complete 30 credits towards an Honors Degree, 24 credits of Masters\' level courses and a 72 credit year long project in the final year. The Honors Courses and the Masters\' level courses may be electives or compulsory courses it depends from department to department. Please find below links to all departments curricula. Please note that these are correct to the best of our knowledge</p>','Curriculum','','publish','open','open','','curriculum','','','2011-03-29 08:54:05','2011-03-29 08:54:05','',0,'http://10.100.5.5/~ugacademics/wordpress/?